{
  "doc_id": "7638",
  "text": "Patterns during Phagocytosis PI3K inhibitors have less effect on phagocytosis of 2-m diameter particles than 5-m particles [CITATION_1] . The differential sensitivity of small and large particle phagocytosis to PI3K inhibition suggests that different signals regulate phagocytosis of small and large particles. We therefore examined whether differences in 3ЈPI synthesis or GTPase activation patterns during phagocytosis of different sizes of particles could explain the size-dependence of inhibition by PI3K inhibitors. Streptavidin-coated silica microspheres of 2-and 5-m diameter were opsonized with equivalent levels of IgG-labeling per unit surface area (see Materials and Methods and Supplemental Figure S1 ). To compare the 3ЈPI responses during phagocytosis, macrophages expressing CFP and a YFP fusion to the PH domain of Akt (YFP-AktPH) were presented opsonized 2-and 5-m microspheres and observed by ratiometric fluorescence imaging. AktPH binds to PI(3,4,5)P 3 and PI(3,4)P 2 [CITATION_2] . Subcellular localization of fluorescent AktPH chimeras has been used previously to localize activity of PI3K [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Quantitative measures of multiple phagocytic events showed that, for both 2-and 5-m phagosomes, the maximum 3ЈPI accumulation appeared ϳ2-3 min after the initiation of pseudopod extension ( Figure  3A) . Thus, phagocytosis of both small and large particles generated robust, localized 3ЈPI responses of similar magnitudes.",
